            content: '<p>Caesar\'s own account of the civil war. Written in the third person (like his Gallic War commentaries), it presents Caesar\'s actions as defensive and his enemies as a corrupt faction. Invaluable as a primary source but deeply partisan — Caesar is both author and protagonist, controlling the narrative entirely.</p><p><strong>Key passages:</strong> The justification for crossing the Rubicon (1.7–9), the speed of the advance through Italy, the account of Pharsalus. Note what Caesar omits or downplays — there is almost no engagement with the constitutional arguments against him.</p><p><strong>Source evaluation:</strong> Always ask: what is Caesar\'s purpose in writing? He is not a neutral historian — he is a general and politician justifying his actions to a Roman audience. The calm, measured prose style is itself a rhetorical strategy: it makes extraordinary actions seem reasonable and inevitable.</p>'
